descript.purpose: The data were collected as part of the Data Preservation Program of the Washington Division of Geology and Earth Resources and subsequently updated as part of the Washington Contribution to the National Geothermal Data System. The aim of the Data Preservation Program is both to organize and preserve various types of geologic data in a digital format and to make it easier for the public to obtain the data. The creation of this dataset was prompted by the need for up-to-date and positionally accurate reporting of known or suspected faults of Quaternary age in the state. It cannot be used to determine the presence or absence of faults beneath any specific locality, and was not intended for use at scales larger than 1:250,000. Such a determination requires a site-specific geotechnical investigation performed by a qualified practitioner.

attracc.attraccr: Cross-checks of index maps contained within the source publications for this dataset were performed as the attribute spreadsheet was generated to ensure location and attribute accuracy between the faults and their respective attribute data. Arcs were spot-checked within the visual display in ArcMap and checked against attribute data in the spreadsheet.

horizpa.horizpar: The accuracy of location of faults within this dataset is largely dependent upon the sources of the data. The accuracy of faults generated by digitizing the extent of individually scanned and georeferenced maps is variable, as differing numbers of control points were available with which to georeference each source map.

procstep.procdesc:
The fault dataset was generated by performing a detailed study of existing literature, georeferencing source maps, digitizing or downloading selected fault locations, and then generating attributes for traces, such as fault name, fault visibility, age of last known deformation, method of detection (lidar, mapping, or geophysical method), and the source used for the fault trace as well as the corresponding ID number of the fault in the USGS Quaternary fault and fold database.
Faults were generated using the largest scale possible, with a 1:250,000 minimum, although a great majority of the source maps were at a scale of 1:100,000 or better. Many fault zones in this dataset contain information from multiple sources. When multiple sources of fault information provided lines representing the same fault trace (not always coincident), consideration was given to the original source map for all publications, as well as potential updates to those maps in subsequent geologic investigations.
The source for only the trace of each fault is provided. It is important to note that for many faults, the sources for detailed paleoseismic studies that provide evidence of Quaternary deformation for each fault are not provided. For a more comprehensive list of sources of detailed information about Quaternary faults, refer to the U.S. Geological Survey's Quaternary fault and fold database (http://earthquake.usgs.gov/hazards/qfaults/).
Version History
Version 3.0 (June, 2011): This dataset was edited for location and attribute. Attribute names were added and/or changed, and metadata for the entire dataset was updated.
Version 2.0 (June, 2010): This dataset was migrated from a shapefile to a geodatabase. Feature class names and attribute names were changed, and metadata for the entire dataset was updated.
Version 1.0 (2008) Original data in shapefile format.

attr.attrdef: Values represent the published dip of a fault

Values represent the published age of the last know rupture on the fault. Historic (<150 years); Latest Quaternary (<15,000 years); Late Quaternary (<130,000 years); Middle and late Quaternary (<750,000 years); Undifferentiated Quaternary (<1.6 million years)
Values represent the published slip rate on a fault. The published rates are presented as <0.2 mm/yr, Between 0.2 - 1.0 mm/y, and Between 1.0 - 5.0 mm/yr.
Values represent the published sense of slip of a fault
Text showing published confidence of a fault trace
Text showing citation (limited to 250 characters) for the source of the line trace of a fault
Values represent the published name of individual faults in Washington State.

Text representative of fault class type assigned by the U.S. Geological Survey. Class A - Geologic evidence demonstrates the existence of a Quaternary fault of tectonic origin, whether the fault is exposed for mapping or inferred from liquefaction or other deformational features. Class B - Geologic evidence demonstrates the existence of a fault or suggests Quaternary deformation, but either (1) the fault might not extend deeply enough to be a potential source of significant earthquakes, or (2) the currently available geologic evidence is too strong to confidently assign the feature to Class C but not strong enough to assign it to Class A. Class C - Geologic evidence is insufficient to demonstrate (1) the existence of tectonic fault, or (2) Quaternary slip or deformation associated with the feature. Class D - Geologic evidence demonstrates that the feature is not a tectonic fault or feature; this category includes features such as demonstrated joints or joint zones, landslides, erosional or fluvial scarps, or landforms resembling fault scarps, but of demonstrable non-tectonic origin.
Text representative of the mapped scale of published fault trace.

dataIdInfo.idPurp: The data were collected as part of an effort to updated and document potential earthquake sources for seismic hazard assessment in the National Seismic Hazard Maps. The aim of the Quaternary fault and fold database is both to organize and preserve various types of geologic data in a digital format and to make it easier for the public to obtain the data. The creation of this dataset was prompted by the need for up-to-date and positionally accurate reporting of known or suspected faults of Quaternary age resulting from newly published peer-reviewed studies in Washington State.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This release is an update to the online "Quaternary fault and fold database" for Washington State. The online database was last updated for Washington in 2014 – this 2020 update includes newly identified and modified traces and geometries for on-shore faults gleaned from new peer-reviewed studies and mapping of active faults within the state of Washington. These data contain lines representing the location of faults with known or suspected Quaternary (<1,600,000 yrs) activity in the state of Washington. This data was complied in conjunction with the Washington State Geological Survey. Significant modifications include: 1) newly mapped active traces of the Sadie Creek fault, Entiat fault system, Spencer Canyon fault system; 2) modified geometry of the Seattle fault zone; and 3) representative lines for the areas of the Mount Saint Helens seismic zone, Western Rainier seismic zone, and Goat Rocks seismic zone.

Faults are attributed following the Quaternary fault and fold database attributes, including information such as age, slip sense, dip direction, class, and mapped scale. This dataset contains multiple interpretations of the same faults or fault systems by different authors, which documented within the attributes.
